  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Increasing safe and dignified living conditions through provision of emergency shelter to internally displaced persons (IDPs) affected by drought in Herat province.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">DRC, through this project, aims to deliver emergency shelter kits (family sized tent with necessary tools for pitching and 2 Tarpaulins) to support drought affected internally displaced people who live in open spaces and makeshift shelters that do not provide dignity, privacy and protection from the elements. DRC participated in the inter-agency joint assessments between May and July 2018, verified 11,802 displaced families (82,614 individuals) and distributed cash for food to a total of 6,910 families while the remaining caseload (4,892 families) was covered by Norwegian Refugee Council (NRC).

Under this action through Afghanistan Humanitarian Fund (AHF), DRC plans to procure and distribute 2,070 emergency shelter kits to displaced families living at Injil IDP settlements in Herat province. DRC intends to cover the additional shelter needs of 2,070 drought affected IDP families (14,490 individuals). A team of community volunteers will be identified, trained on shelter program and in turn provide support to female headed families, families with large number children, disabled and critical illness in erection of shelters. The shelter needs are higher than the planned response under this action and DRC will collaborate with other partners (NGOs and UN agencies) to ensure a coordinated and effective approach to the provision of shelter assistance to address the additional needs. The assessment report and mapping of responses from all actors show that there will still be a gap of about 3,000 families in dire need of shelter support even after this allocation.

To ensure service provision in a dignified manner, DRC has an accountability framework as part of its action plan to comply with common humanitarian standards (CHS) that will be used as a benchmark to guide its quality implementation along with ES/NFI cluster guidelines. Shelter is a key protection priority. This project will have a direct impact on the protective environment in informal IDP settlements. DRC will mainstream protection throughout project implementation to minimize secondary protection risks. 

The project duration is 6 months active from 16 September 2018 to 15 March 2019.</narrative>
  </description>
